{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Related WorkRecent discoveries in deep learning have improved the automatic classification of oral lesions using photographic imagery.",
    "Al-Ali et al. [1] extend this line of work by developing CLASEG, a multiclass classification framework based on EfficientNet-B3 and trained on 2,072 clinical images across 14 types of lesions.",
    "Their algorithm demonstrated a classification accuracy of 74.49%, cementing the clinical utility of consumer grade images to classify oral lesions into benign, premalignant and malignant categories, and deviated from earlier studies which focused on binary classification or demanded expensive imaging modalities.",
    "While most studies have centered on multiclass prediction problems, CLASEG focused on classes within a single image.",
    "We adopt this approach and implement EfficientNetV2B1 to develop a streamlined pipeline comprising stratified sampling, purpose-driven augmentation, and class-balanced training."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Al-Ali et al. [1] extend this line of work by developing CLASEG, a multiclass classification framework based on EfficientNet-B3 and trained on 2,072 clinical images across 14 types of lesions."
  ]
}